  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Somalia Drought Joint Response 2022 (DRA)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">SC and local partner GREDO will cover Berdale and Burhakaba districts with emergency water trucking and cash transfers to meet lifesaving basic needs of most vulnerable households. Community sensitization and hygiene promotion will be conducted with a focus on prevention of AWD/cholera transmission. Water Management Committees will be established and trained to support regular water quality monitoring, hygiene promotion, and emergency water distribution. Based on SC&#x2019;s evidenced-based Common Approach, cash transfers will be tied with behavior change communication on infant and young child feeding practices.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">SC will target the most vulnerable agro-pastoralist and displaced households (HHs) facing severe water shortages in hard-to-reach areas, using agreed vulnerability criteria (HHs with Pregnant and Lactating Women, children under five; child-headed, women-headed or elderly-headed HHs; and HHs with members with a disability).</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Somalia is facing a critical drought following three consecutive failed rainy seasons. Bay region in South West State (SWS) has the 2nd highest number of people (377,000) affected by severe water shortages with severe to extreme drought conditions. 369,780 people are currently in Crisis (IPC Phase 3) and 83,670 in Emergency (IPC Phase 4).  According to a December 2021 drought assessment in SWS, 91% of communities reduced their water consumption in the previous 4 weeks. The main challenges faced in accessing water are distance to water point, lack of money, unavailability of water, overcrowded water points and water quality.   Needs across districts of Bay region are high with relatively low humanitarian support currently provided.</narrative>
  </description>
